\begin_layout Standard
Using a Digital Signal Processing (DSP) Radio Module with an antenna,
 we can reliably pick up on FM radiowaves.
 The DSP uses I2C to send carrier information to the microcontroller.
 Namely,
 we are interested in the Radio Data System (RDS),
 which encodes information in the FM signal,
 namely the song title and playing artist.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The DSP also manages an analog path to the amplifier and speaker assembly over I2C.
 Any signals sent to the DSP (mute,
 volume up,
 volume down,
 etc) will be interpreted by the DSP and sent to the speaker.
 The amplifier boosts the gain on our speaker.
 An FM antenna will be attached to ensure clear FM signal inference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DSP's I2C also relays the RDS metadata,
 which will be inputted to the LastFM API.
 HTTP GET responses will fetch relevant song & artist information from the website.
 Thus this I2C SDA will both provide 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 receive data (provide LastFM input,
 receive requests to manipulate speaker volume).
 The DSP will also need two 4.7 kiloOhm resistors on it's I2C lines to ensure reliable response.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Universal Remote and IR Receiver components are identical to Lab 3,
 but we will modify the multi-tap text algorithm further to meet the specifications indicated in Section 
